<div id="review_331434487" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/331434487" />
    <a title="╟ ♫ Tima ♪ ╣ ♥" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1362704-tima"><img alt="╟ ♫ Tima ♪ ╣ ♥" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606239932p2/1362704.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/331434487?book_show_action=true">May 17, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="╟ ♫ Tima ♪ ╣ ♥" class="user" itemprop="url" name="╟ ♫ Tima ♪ ╣ ♥" href="/user/show/1362704-tima">╟ ♫ Tima ♪ ╣ ♥</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">early readers, beginners, 2nd grade</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to ╟ ♫ Tima ♪ ╣ ♥ by: </span>
      My 3rd grade teacher
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1362704-tima?shelf=genre-young-adult">genre-young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1362704-tima?shelf=read-in-childhood">read-in-childhood</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1362704-tima?shelf=2-stars">2-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1362704-tima?shelf=read-in-2012">read-in-2012</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1362704-tima?shelf=genre-historical-fiction">genre-historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer331434487" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9086369043178986999">When I read this book at a much younger age, I adored it. Let&apos;s be real, I probably had an unrealistic crush on the fictional Attean. Tall, dark, handsome, strong, intelligent, good with hands... ;)<br/><br/>Alright, alright so he is 14 in this book, but I was merely a young lass enamored with the idea of a gorgeous Native American boy to sweep me off my feet.<br/><br/><br/><i>Now about the book itself</i>... It is an easy read for 2nd-5th graders, I would say. It doesn&apos;t teach much but the plot is catching enough that young r</span>
  <span id="freeText9086369043178986999" style="display:none">When I read this book at a much younger age, I adored it. Let's be real, I probably had an unrealistic crush on the fictional Attean. Tall, dark, handsome, strong, intelligent, good with hands... ;)<br /><br />Alright, alright so he is 14 in this book, but I was merely a young lass enamored with the idea of a gorgeous Native American boy to sweep me off my feet.<br /><br /><br /><i>Now about the book itself</i>... It is an easy read for 2nd-5th graders, I would say. It doesn't teach much but the plot is catching enough that young readers would devour it. A young boy's father leaves him alone in a cabin surrounded by nothing but forest while he returns to Quincy, Maine to retrieve his wife and child. In his absence, Matt [boy] meets Attean [Indian] and against all odds, they become friends. As things progress, he is invited to join the tribe in their move West. Does he abandon the cabin he's guarded for almost a year or does he wait for his family's return? *cue dramatic music* You'll just have to read it to find out! <br /><br />What I don't like is the inconsistent writing. The author used very ridiculous speech for the Indians. "Me Attean. We no like white man. White man words bad". She gives the boy's father a type of hybrid old-english-southern-alabama accent, while Matt's is plain ol' english. At times, she uses modern slang such as : "the village was awesome" and "now it looks lame".<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9086369043178986999" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


